CMake is a mature utility for building software
projects. CMake works by generating Makefiles
for the host machine from platform and compiler
independent configuration files that describe the
build process, rather than script it.

A CMake configuration file, called a CMakeLists.txt, describes the recipe for building a component. This description includes: compiler options (e.g. defaulting REAL to an 8-byte wide type), compiler definitions (e.g. defining GEOS_FP to use GEOS-FP met fields), files to compile, and a list of dependencies. The CMake engine reads these configuration files, solves the dependencies, and then generates a Makefile structure for compiling the entire project.

This work is PR #XX on the GEOS-Chem GitHub page (https://github.com/geoschem/geos-chem/pull/XX) and is scheduled to be ready to merge at the end of May. Once it is merged, you will be able to build GEOS-Chem Classic and GCHP with CMake! The existing Makefile-based build system is not going to be removed, nor will any compiler or software dependencies compatibility change. Once this work is merged, I will be actively supporting related questions and issues, so please don’t hesitate to submit issues on GitHub or contact with me directly.

A priority of the GCHP working group is improving the accessibility of GCHP by making it easier to use. Currently, one barrier to using GCHP is compiling—particularly for first-time users. Building GCHP is significantly more complicated then GEOS-Chem Classic because of the new dependencies introduced by GCHP. The GEOS-Chem Classic repository contains 365 Fortran files. The GCHP repository contains more than 3000 Fortran, C, and C++ files. The shear volume of code in GCHP means that maintaining the GCHP build system takes considerable effort.

This work aims to reduce the burden of maintaining GEOS-Chem’s build system for developers, while simplifying the process of compiling GEOS-Chem Classic and GCHP for users, using the popular utility CMake. This development implements the necessary files so that CMake can be used to build GCHP and GEOS-Chem Classic. This work is scheduled to be ready to merge at the end of May and is PR #XX on the GEOS-Chem’s GitHub page.

The flow of the Makefile-based GCHP build is illustrated below. Each component’s Makefile calls the Makefiles of all it’s dependencies. These relationships can be difficult to maintain for third-party subcomponents like MAPL.

With the CMake-based build system, each component’s CMakeLists.txt describes to the CMake engine how it is built and it's dependencies. The CMake engine generates the Makefile structure for compiling GCHP.
